# Cell Passage Protocol

## Overview

This protocol describes the routine passage of adherent mammalian cells (HEK-293T) for maintenance culture.

## Materials

- [ ] HEK-293T cells (80% confluent in T-75 flask)
- [ ] Warm PBS (37°C)
- [ ] Warm Trypsin-EDTA (0.25%, 37°C)
- [ ] Complete growth medium (DMEM + 10% FBS)
- [ ] Hemocytometer or automated cell counter

## Procedure

### 1. Pre-warm Reagents

 Incubate PBS, Trypsin-EDTA, and growth medium in 37°C water bath for 15-30 minutes.

### 2. Aspirate Medium

1. Observe cell morphology under microscope
2. Note: Cells should be 80-90% confluent
3. Aspirate spent medium from flask

### 3. Wash Cells

1. Add 5 mL PBS to flask
2. Gently rock to wash cell surface
3. Aspirate PBS

### 4. Trypsinization

1. Add 2 mL Trypsin-EDTA to flask
2. Incubate at 37°C for 3-5 minutes
3. Tap flask to dislodge cells
4. Observe under microscope - cells should be rounded

### 5. Neutralize and Count

1. Add 8 mL complete medium to neutralize trypsin
2. Pipette up and down to create single-cell suspension
3. Count cells using hemocytometer

### 6. Passage

1. Seed at 1:4 to 1:10 split ratio
2. Add appropriate volume to new flask
3. Top up with fresh medium to final volume

## Notes

- Passage number: P15-P20 recommended
- Do not let cells become over-confluent
- Change medium every 2-3 days
